# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cable-tie
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cable-tie/binding-knot] A **binding knot** is a knot that may be used to keep an object or multiple loose objects together, using a string or a rope that passes at least once around them.
[src:cable-tie/binding-knot] There are various binding knots, divided into two types.
[src:cable-tie/binding-knot] **Friction knots** are held in place by the friction between the windings of line.
[src:cable-tie/binding-knot] **Knotted-ends knots** are held in place by the two ends of the line being knotted together.
[src:cable-tie/binding-knot] Whipping and seizing are binding knots, but are more complex since they contain many turns, like a lashing.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] A **buckle** or **clasp** is a device used for fastening two loose ends, with one end attached to it and the other held by a catch in a secure but adjustable manner.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Often taken for granted, the invention of the buckle was indispensable in securing two ends before the invention of the zipper.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The basic buckle frame comes in a variety of shapes and sizes depending on the intended use and fashion of the era.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Buckles are as much in use today as they have been in the past: used for much more than just securing one's belt, instead they are one of the most dependable devices in securing a range of items.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The word "buckle" enters Middle English via Old French and the Latin *buccula* or "cheek-strap," as for a helmet.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Some of the earliest buckles known are those used by Roman soldiers to strap their body armor together and prominently on the balteus and cingulum.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Made out of bronze and expensive, these buckles were purely functional for their strength and durability - vital to the individual soldier.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The baldric was a later belt worn diagonally over the right shoulder down to the waist at the left carrying the sword, and its buckle therefore was as important as that on a Roman soldier’s armor.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Bronze Roman buckles cames in various types.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Not only used for practical purposes, these buckles were also decorated.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] A Type I Roman buckle was a “buckle-plate” either decorated or plain and consisted of geometric ornaments.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Type IA Roman buckles were similar to Type I buckles but differed by being long and narrow, made of double sheet metal, and attached to small D-shaped buckles (primarily had dolphin-heads as decorations).
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Type IB “buckle-loops” were even more similar to Type IA buckles, the only difference being that instead of dolphin-heads, they were adorned with horse-heads.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] There were also Type II buckles (Type IIA and Type IIB) used by Romans, but all types of Roman buckles could have served purposes for simple clothing as well, and predominantly, as a military purpose.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Aside from the practical use found in Roman buckles, Scythian and Sarmatian buckles incorporated animal motifs that were characteristic to their respective decorative arts.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] These motifs often represented animals engaged in mortal combat.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] These motifs were imported by many Germanic peoples and the belt buckles were evident in the graves of the Franks and Burgundies.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Throughout the Middle Ages, the buckle was used mostly for ornamentation until the second half of the 14th century where the knightly belt and buckle took on its most splendid form.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Buckles remained exclusively for the wealthy until the 15th century where improved manufacturing techniques made it possible to easily produce a cheaper molded item available to the general population.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] During the Middle Ages, buckles were made by dedicated smiths known as bucklemakers, or 'senkelære' in Middle Low German.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The road of Bucklemaker Wynd in Dundee, Scotland (now Victoria Road), was named for being where the bucklemakers lived.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] However, much of their trade was eventually picked up by other 'hammermen', including jewellers, and the bucklemaker's trade slowly fell out of notice.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The buckle essentially consists of four main components: the frame, chape, bar, and prong.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The oldest Roman buckles are of a simple D-shaped frame, in which the prong or tongue extends from one side to the other.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] In the 14th century, buckles with a double-loop or "8"-shaped frame emerged.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The prongs of these buckles attach to the center post.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The appearance of multi-part buckles with chapes and removable pins, which were commonly found on shoes, occurred in the 17th century.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The frame is the most visible part of the buckle and holds the other parts of the buckle together.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Buckle frames come in various shapes, sizes, and decorations.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The shape of the frame could be a plain square or rectangle, but may be oval or made into a circular shape.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] A reverse curve of the frame indicated that the whole buckle was intended to be used for securing a thick material, such as leather.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] This reverse curve shape made it easier to thread the intended thick material end over the bar.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] But the shape of the frame is not limited to simply squares and ovals, the decoration of the frame itself defines the shape it will turn out to be.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Since the frame is the largest part of the buckle, any and all decorations are placed on it.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Decorations range from wedged shapes, picture references to people and animals, and insignia of a desired organization.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The part of the frame that strap goes through prior to putting the tongue/prong through the hole is often referred to as the 'end bar'.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The 'center bar' holds the tongue and the part (if present) that holds the tip of the strap in place is called the 'keeper' or 'keeper bar' these terms are used when additional information is needed to describe a buckle for measurements or design.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Note that if a separate piece of leather or metal is attached to the strap for holding the tip of the belt/strap in place that is sometimes also called a 'keeper'.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Chapes or "caps" of various designs could be fitted to the bar to enable one strap end to be secured before fastening the other, adjustable end.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] This made buckles easily removable and interchangeable, leading to a significant advantage since buckles were expensive.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Unfortunately, the teeth or spikes on the semi-circular chapes damaged the straps or belts, making frequent repairs of the material necessary.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Buckles fitted with "T"-, anchor-, or spade-shaped chapes avoided this problem but needed a slotted end in the belt to accommodate them.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The belt buckle chapes are frequently made in a form of a plate, thus the name buckle plate.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The prong (also named pin) is typically made out of steel or other types of metal.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] In conventional belts, the prong fits through the buckle to secure the material at a pre-set length.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The prong is usually referred to as the tongue of the buckle in America, as in 'lock-tongued buckle'.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Prong is only used when the tongue is permanently fixed in position.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The bar serves to hold the chape and prong to the frame.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] When prongs and chapes are removed from the buckle design, the buckle incorporated a movable bar relying on the tension of the adjusted belt to keep it in place.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The first known buckles to be used were made out of bronze for their strength and durability for military usage.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] For the last few hundred years, buckles have been made from brass (an alloy of copper and zinc).
[src:cable-tie/buckle] In the 18th century, brass buckles incorporated iron bars, chapes, and prongs due to the parts being made by different manufactures.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Silver was also used in buckle manufacturing for its malleability and for being strong and durable with an attractive shine.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] White metal, any bright metallic compound, was also used in all styles of buckles; however, if iron was present, rust will form if it is allowed to be exposed and remain in damp conditions.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Pearl buckles have been made from pearly shells and usually for ladies’ dresses.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Since a reasonable size flat surface was needed to make a buckle, oyster was commonly used to make these types of buckles.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The quality and color of course vary, ranging from layers of yellow and white to brown or grey.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] When preferred materials were scarce during the Great Depression of the 1930s and the two World Wars, buckles became a low priority and manufactures needed to find ways to continue to produce them cheaply.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Makers turned to wood as a cheap alternative since it was easily worked by hand or simple machinery by impressing the designs onto the wood.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Any attempt to brighten the wood’s dull appearance with painted designs or plasterwork embellishments immediately came off if the buckle were to be washed.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Buckles were not entirely made out of leather because a frame and bar of leather would not be substantial enough to carry a prong or the full weight of the belt and anything the belt and buckle intend to support.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] However, leather (or dyed suede, more common to match a lady’s garment color) was used more as a “cover-up” for cheap materials to create a product worthy of buying.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Buckles were not made out of glass; rather the glass was used as a decorative feature that covered the entire frame of a metal buckle.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] One method of creating glass buckles was gluing individual discs of glass to the metal frame.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Another more intricate method was to set a wire into the back of a glass disc, and then threading the wire through a hole in the fretted frame of the buckle.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The glass was further secured by either bending it over the back of the frame or splayed out like a rivet.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Celluloid, a type of thermoplastic invented in 1869, was used sparingly and only for decoration until after World War I where it began to be produced on a wider commercial scale.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] After World War II, the chemical industry saw a great expansion where Celluloid and other plastics such as Casein and Bakelite formed the basis of the buckle-making industry.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Many thermoplastic polymers such as nylon are now used in snap-fit buckles for a wide variety of applications.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Although any device that serves to secure two loose ends is casually called a buckle, if it consists of two separate pieces with one for a hook and the other for a loop, it should be called a clasp.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Clasps became increasingly popular at the turn of the 19th century with one clear disadvantage: since each belt end was fixed to each clasp piece, the size of the belt was typically not adjustable unless an elastic panel was inserted.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] A buckle without a chape or prongs is called a buckle trim or slide.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] It may have been designed this particular way or it may have lost its prongs through continuous use.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] This type was frequently used in home dress-making (belt end being secured with the simple hook-and-eye) and was purely used for decoration for items such as shoe fronts to conceal unattractive elastic fitting.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The belt buckle is the conventional buckle with a frame, bar and prong gives the most reliable and easy-to-use closure for a belt.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] It is not meant, by design, to offer much space for decoration, but for its time-tested reliability.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] A conventional snap-fit buckle that is formed by a "male" buckle member—the hook end—and a "female" buckle member—the insertion end.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The male buckle member consists of a center rod and two spring prongs equally spaced from the center rod.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The two spring arms each have a retaining block that terminates at the front end.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The female buckle member has a front open side and two side holes which hold and secure the two spring arms of the male buckle member.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] This sort of buckle may be found connecting many strapped items such as pet harnesses, safety harnesses, personal flotation jackets, fanny packs and other bags, belts, gun slings, and boots.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] It is also known as the "parachute buckle" or "fastex buckle".
[src:cable-tie/buckle] They are often used in conjunction with tri-glide slides.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] The modern side-release version of the buckle was developed and patented in 1977 by Richard Tracy while working for ITW Nexus, a division of Illinois Tool Works that produced the Fastex line of plastic fasteners.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] In the United States, during the American Civil War of the 1860s, some members of the military wore brass belt buckles.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] These buckles had a pin that was inserted directly into the belt, thus not having any moving parts.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] In 1920, this type of buckle was awarded to winners of professional rodeo contests at the San Francisco Cow Palace in California.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Throughout the 1920s and later, they were used as trophies awarded to champions of bull riding, barrel racing, steer roping, bronc riding and other rodeo skill competitions.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] By the 1950s, Hollywood Westerns featured cowboys wearing large, shiny belt buckles and this influenced country/western fashion.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] During the 1990s, country/western dance competitions mirrored the practice by awarding championship buckles to their dance champions.
[src:cable-tie/buckle] Modern-day western belt buckles are commonly made of silver, brass, pewter, zinc alloy, or stainless steel.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] Cable lacing uses a thin cord, which is traditionally made of waxed linen, to bind together a group of cables using a series of running lockstitches.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] Flat lacing tapes made of modern materials such as nylon, polyester, Teflon, fiberglass, and Nomex are also available with a variety of coatings to improve knot holding.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] The lacing begins and ends with a whipping or other knot to secure the free ends.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] Wraps are spaced relative to the overall harness diameter to maintain the wiring in a tight, neat bundle, and the ends are then neatly trimmed.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] In addition to continuous or running lacing, there are a variety of lacing patterns used in different circumstances.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] In some cases stand-alone knots called **spot ties** are also used.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] For lashing large cables and cable bundles to support structures in telecommunications applications, there are three named cable lacing styles: the box stitch, the Chicago stitch, and the Kansas City stitch.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] The Kansas City and Chicago stitches are adapted to multiple cables; each forms the cables into a rectangular structure by wrapping wax string around each pair within the bundle.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] They both require a cable sewing needle to tie, such as the Jonard 2257 or 3209, or an Evans needle like Jonard 287.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] The needle is used by pushing its blade through the bundle, inserting the wax string through its loop, and drawing it with the wax string back through the bundle.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] The Chicago stitch can be used to bind cables in free space, or to bind them to a support; in the latter case, the stitch is started by tying around the support, and then the Chicago stitch is performed as though in free space.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] The Kansas City stitch lays the bundle flat against the support, and each internal wrapping in the bundle also wraps the support.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] The box stitch is suited to one or few cables, and is suited to binding a large cable or a small number of cables to a support.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] It will make a cylindrical structure rather than a rectangle, but it is less time-consuming, and it does not require a tool.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] Some organizations have in-house standards to which cable lacing must conform, for example NASA specifies its cable lacing techniques in chapter 9 of NASA-STD-8739.4.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] Archived from the original on December 1, 2007.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] "Qwest Corporation Technical Publication - Telecommunications Equipment Installation Guidelines" (PDF). pp.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] *GTE Telephone Operations (December 1991).
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] See "External links" section for these documents.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] "Workmanship and Design Practices for Electronic Equipment". pp.
[src:cable-tie/cable-lacing] *"Cable and Harness - General Requirements".
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] A **cable tie** (also known as a **hose tie**, **panduit**, **tie wrap**, **wire tie**, or **zip tie**) is a type of fastener for holding items together, primarily electrical cables and wires.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Because of their low cost, ease of use, and binding strength, cable ties are ubiquitous, finding use in a wide range of other applications.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Cable ties were first manufactured by Thomas & Betts under the brand name **Ty-Rap**.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The common cable tie, normally made of nylon, has a flexible tape section with teeth that engage with a pawl in the head to form a ratchet so that as the free end of the tape section is pulled the cable tie tightens and does not come undone.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] When the mouthpiece is inserted through the grooves and pulled tight, it creates a secure, adjustable loop, which locks in place like a knot.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Some ties include a tab that can be depressed to release the ratchet so that the tie can be loosened or removed, and possibly reused.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Stainless steel versions, some coated with rugged plastic, have been developed for exterior applications and hazardous environments.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The most common cable tie comprises a flexible nylon tape with an integrated linear ratchet gear rack, and on one end a pawl within a small open case.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Once the pointed tip of the cable tie has been pulled through the case and past the ratchet, it is prevented from being pulled back unless a large amount of force is applied; the resulting loop may only be pulled tighter.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] This allows several cables to be bound into a cable bundle and/or to form a cable tree.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] A cable tie tensioning device or tool may apply a cable tie with a specific tension.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The tool may cut off the extra tail flush with the head in order to avoid a sharp edge which might otherwise cause injury.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Light-duty tools are operated by squeezing the handle with the fingers, while heavy-duty versions can be powered by compressed air or a solenoid to prevent repetitive strain injury.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] To increase resistance to ultraviolet light in outdoor applications, nylon containing a minimum of 2% carbon black is used to protect the polymer chains and extend the cable tie's service life.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Blue cable ties are supplied to the food industry and contain a metal additive so they can be detected by industrial metal detectors.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Cable ties made of ETFE (Tefzel) are used in radiation-rich environments.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Red cable ties made of ECTFE (Halar) are used for plenum cabling.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Stainless steel cable ties are also available for flameproof applications—coated stainless ties are available to prevent galvanic attack from dissimilar metals (e.g. zinc-coated cable tray).
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Plastic handcuffs are based on the cable tie design and are used by law enforcement to restrain prisoners.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Cable ties are also sometimes used to prevent hubcaps (also known as wheel trims) from falling off a moving vehicle, and some are sold specifically for this purpose.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The use of cable ties in medicolegal cases is infrequent, being involved in situations of neck compression or restraint.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Cable ties were invented by Thomas & Betts, an electrical company, in 1958 under the brand name Ty-Rap.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Initially, they were designed for airplane wire harnesses.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The original design used a metal tooth, and these can still be obtained.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Manufacturers later changed to the nylon/plastic design.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Over the years the design has been extended and developed into many spin-off products.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] One example was a self-locking loop developed as an alternative to purse-string suture in colon anastomosis.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The Ty-Rap cable tie's inventor, Maurus C.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Logan, worked for Thomas & Betts and finished his career with the company as Vice President of Research and Development.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] During his tenure at Thomas & Betts, he contributed to the development and marketing of many successful Thomas & Betts products.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Logan died on 12 November 2007, at age 86.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] The idea for the cable tie came to Logan while touring a Boeing aircraft manufacturing facility in 1956.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Aircraft wiring was a cumbersome and detailed undertaking, involving thousands of feet of wire organized on sheets of 50-foot-long plywood and held in place with knotted, wax-coated, braided nylon cord.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Each knot had to be pulled tight by wrapping the cord around one's finger, which sometimes cut the operator's fingers until they developed thick calluses.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Logan was convinced there had to be an easier, more forgiving way to accomplish this critical task.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] For the next couple of years, Logan experimented with various tools and materials.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] On June 24, 1958, a patent for the Ty-Rap cable tie was submitted.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Cable ties are generally designed as single-use devices; however, they can be reopened with little or no damage by inserting a small flat object between the ratchet and the pawl, and pulling the pawl out.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Some models have a mechanism to release the pawl and allow re-use.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Alternatively, the tie can be twisted 180 degrees and inserted into the case upside down to create a weaker loop that can be easily opened by hand, but still strong enough for certain simple tasks, such as holding several cables together.
[src:cable-tie/cable-tie] Other methods of bundling cable together securely and semi-permanently include cable lacing, strapping, binding knots such as the surgeon's knot or constrictor knot, Velcro brand hook-and-loop strips, conveyor belt hooks, twist ties, Rapstrap fasteners, or metal buckle.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] Guitarist and lead vocalist Jenny McKechnie moved to Melbourne from Bendigo with a background in folk music, and was introduced to the city's burgeoning punk music scene by a friend, Grace Kindellan, who formed a band (Wet Lips) with McKechnie on bass guitar.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] McKechnie joined bassist Nick Brown and drummer Shauna Boyle to form Cable Ties in 2015, with the band naming itself after cable ties in reference to the band's "very physical but functional" sound.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] They played their earliest gigs at The Tote Hotel in Collingwood and The Old Bar in Fitzroy, and their debut studio album, the eponymous *Cable Ties* was released in May 2017.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] The band is signed to Melbourne independent record label Poison City Records.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] Their second studio album, *Far Enough*, was released internationally on American label Merge Records in March 2020.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] In March 2022, Cable Ties announced the release of their third studio album, *All Her Plans*, released on 23 June 2023.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] In an album review, Alex Gallagher from *NME* said "Cable Ties just keep getting better.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] The Music Victoria Awards, are an annual awards night celebrating Victorian music.
[src:cable-tie/cable-ties-band] The National Live Music Awards (NLMAs) commenced in 2016 to recognise contributions to the live music industry in Australia.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black is used as a colorant and reinforcing filler in tires and other rubber products and as a pigment and wear protection additive in plastics, paints, and ink pigment.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It is used in the EU as a food colorant when produced from vegetable matter (E153).
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The current International Agency for Research on Cancer (IARC) evaluation is that, "Carbon black is possibly carcinogenic to humans (Group 2B)".
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Short-term exposure to high concentrations of carbon black dust may produce discomfort to the upper respiratory tract through mechanical irritation.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The most common use (70%) of carbon black is as a reinforcing phase in automobile tires.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black also helps conduct heat away from the tread and belt area of the tire, reducing thermal damage and increasing tire life.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Its low cost makes it a common addition to cathodes and anodes and is considered a safe replacement to lithium metal in lithium-ion batteries.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] About 20% of world production goes into belts, hoses, and other non-tire rubber goods.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The remaining 10% use of carbon black comes from pigment in inks, coatings, and plastics, as well as being used as a conductive additive in lithium-ion batteries.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black is added to polypropylene because it absorbs ultraviolet radiation, which otherwise causes the material to degrade.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black particles are also employed in some radar absorbent materials, in photocopier and laser printer toner, and in other inks and paints.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The high tinting strength and stability of carbon black has also provided use in coloring of resins and films.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black has been used in various applications for electronics.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] A good conductor of electricity, carbon black is used as a filler mixed in plastics, elastomer, films, adhesives, and paints.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It is used as an antistatic additive agent in automobile fuel caps and pipes.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black from vegetable origin is used as a food coloring, known in Europe as additive **E153**.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It is approved for use as additive **153** (Carbon blacks or Vegetable carbon) in Australia and New Zealand but has been banned in the US.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The color pigment carbon black has been widely used for many years in food and beverage packaging.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It is used in multi-layer UHT milk bottles in the US, parts of Europe and Asia, and South Africa, and in items like microwavable meal trays and meat trays in New Zealand.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The Canadian Government's extensive review of carbon black in 2011 concluded that carbon black could continue to be used in products – including food packaging for consumers – in Canada.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Within Australasia, the color pigment carbon black in packaging must comply with the requirements of either the EU or US packaging regulations.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] If any colorant is used, it must meet European partial agreement AP(89)1.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Global consumption of carbon black, estimated at 13.2 million metric tons, valued at US$13.7 billion, in 2015, is expected to reach 13.9 million metric tons, valued at US$14.4 billion in 2016.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] While distinct from soot and similar particulates, carbon black can be used as a model compound for diesel soot to better understand how diesel soot behaves under various reaction conditions.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black and diesel soot have some similar properties such as particle sizes, densities, and copolymer adsorption abilities that contribute to them having similar behaviours under various reactions such as oxidation experiments.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Global consumption is forecast to maintain a CAGR (compound annual growth rate) of 5.6% between 2016 and 2022, reaching 19.2 million metric tons, valued at US$20.4 billion, by 2022.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The highest volume use of carbon black is as a reinforcing filler in rubber products, especially tires.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] While a pure gum vulcanization of styrene-butadiene has a tensile strength of no more than 2 MPa and negligible abrasion resistance, compounding it with 50% carbon black by weight improves its tensile strength and wear resistance as shown in the table below.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It is used often in the aerospace industry in elastomers for aircraft vibration control components such as engine mounts.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Practically all rubber products where tensile and abrasion wear properties are important use carbon black, so they are black in color.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Where physical properties are important but colors other than black are desired, such as white tennis shoes, precipitated or fumed silica has been substituted for carbon black.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Silica-based fillers are also gaining market share in automotive tires because they provide better trade-off for fuel efficiency and wet handling due to a lower rolling loss.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Traditionally silica fillers had worse abrasion wear properties, but the technology has gradually improved to a point where they can match carbon black abrasion performance.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black (Color Index International, PBK-7) is the name of a common black pigment, traditionally produced from charring organic materials such as wood or bone.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It appears black because it reflects very little light in the visible part of the spectrum, with an albedo near zero.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The actual albedo varies depending on the source material and method of production.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] All of these types of carbon black were used extensively as paint pigments since prehistoric times.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Rembrandt, Vermeer, Van Dyck, and more recently, Cézanne, Picasso and Manet employed carbon black pigments in their paintings.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] A typical example is Manet's "Music in the Tuileries", where the black dresses and the men's hats are painted in ivory black.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Newer methods of producing carbon black have largely superseded these traditional sources.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] For artisanal purposes, carbon black produced by any means remains common.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] All carbon blacks have chemisorbed oxygen complexes (i.e., carboxylic, quinonic, lactonic, phenolic groups and others) on their surfaces to varying degrees depending on the conditions of manufacture.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] These surface oxygen groups are collectively referred to as volatile content.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] It is also known to be a non-conductive material due to its volatile content.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The coatings and inks industries prefer grades of carbon black that are acid-oxidized.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Acid is sprayed in high-temperature dryers during the manufacturing process to change the inherent surface chemistry of the black.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The amount of chemically-bonded oxygen on the surface area of the black is increased to enhance performance characteristics.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black is a common conductive additive for lithium-ion batteries as the particles have small sizes and a large specific surface areas (SSA) which allow for the additive to be well distributed throughout the cathode or anode in addition to being cheap and long-lasting.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Unlike graphite, which is one of the other common materials used in chargeable batteries, carbon black consists of crystal lattices that are further apart and promotes Li+ intercalation because it allows more pathways for lithium storage.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black has a low density that allows for a large volume of it to be dispersed so that its conductive effects are applied evenly throughout the battery.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Furthermore, its arrangement of randomly distributed graphite-like crystals improves battery stability because of the decrease in the potential barrier of lithium intercalation into graphite, which ultimately affects the performance of cathodes.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] While carbon black is lightweight and well dispersed throughout the battery and increases the conductive performance of batteries, it also contains oxygen containing hydrophilic functional groups that can cause side reactions to occur in the battery and lead to the decomposition of electrolyte.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Graphitization (heating) of carbon black can thermally decompose the hydrophilic functional groups and thus increase the cycle life of the battery which maintains the conductive abilities of carbon black while mitigating the damage that can be caused to batteries by hydrophilic functional groups.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Carbon black is considered *possibly carcinogenic to humans* and classified as a Group 2B carcinogen because there is sufficient evidence in experimental animals with inadequate evidence in human epidemiological studies.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The evidence of carcinogenicity in animal studies comes from two chronic inhalation studies and two intratracheal instillation studies in rats, which showed significantly elevated rates of lung cancer in exposed animals.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] An inhalation study on mice did not show significantly elevated rates of lung cancer in exposed animals.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Epidemiologic data comes from three cohort studies of carbon black production workers.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Two studies, from the United Kingdom and Germany, with over 1,000 workers in each study group showed elevated mortality from lung cancer.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] A third study of over 5,000 carbon black workers in the United States did not show elevated mortality.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Newer findings of increased lung cancer mortality in an update from the UK study suggest that carbon black could be a late-stage carcinogen.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] However, a more recent and larger study from Germany did not confirm this hypothesis.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] There are strict guidelines available and in place to ensure employees who manufacture carbon black are not at risk of inhaling unsafe doses of carbon black in its raw form.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] Respiratory personal protective equipment is recommended to properly protect workers from inhalation of carbon black.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The recommended type of respiratory protection varies depending on the concentration of carbon black used.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] People can be exposed to carbon black in the workplace by inhalation and contact with the skin or eyes.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set the legal limit (Permissible exposure limit) for carbon black exposure in the workplace at 3.5 mg/m3 over an 8-hour workday.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] The National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) has set a Recommended exposure limit (REL) of 3.5 mg/m3 over an 8-hour workday.
[src:cable-tie/carbon-black] At levels of 1750 mg/m3, carbon black is immediately dangerous to life and health.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The **constrictor knot** is one of the most effective binding knots.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Simple and secure, it is a harsh knot that can be difficult or impossible to untie once tightened.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] It is made similarly to a clove hitch but with one end passed under the other, forming an overhand knot under a riding turn.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The **double constrictor knot** is an even more robust variation that features two riding turns.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] First called "constrictor knot" in Clifford Ashley's 1944 work *The Ashley Book of Knots*, this knot likely dates back much further.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Although Ashley seemed to imply that he had invented the constrictor knot over 25 years before publishing *The Ashley Book of Knots*, research indicates that he was not its only originator, but his Book of Knots does seem to be the source of subsequent knowledge and awareness of the knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Although the description is not entirely without ambiguity, the constrictor knot is thought to have appeared under the name "gunner's knot" in the 1866 work *The Book of Knots*, written under the pseudonym Tom Bowling.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The knot is described in relation to the clove hitch, which he illustrated and called the "builder's knot".
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Burgess copied from Bowling, he changed this text to merely state "when the ends are knotted, the builder's knot becomes the gunner's Knot." Although a clove hitch with knotted ends *is* a workable binding knot, Burgess was not actually describing the constrictor knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Hyatt Verrill illustrated Burgess's clove hitch variation in *Knots, Splices and Rope Work*.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The constrictor knot was clearly described but not pictured as the "*timmerknut*" ("timber knot") in the 1916 (2nd) edition of the Swedish book **Om Knutar** ("On Knots") by Hjalmar Öhrvall.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Finnish scout leader Martta Ropponen presented the knot in her 1931 scouting handbook **Solmukirja** ("Knot Book"), one of the first published works known to contain an illustration of the constrictor knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] But even this explicit occurrence of the constrictor remains in doubt, as the name "whip knot" is not applied to the constrictor in other works, and otherwise is used for the strangle knot, tied in the ends of whip tails.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Also in 1931 – and so of essentially same date as for Ropponen – James Drew presented the constrictor (as a strangle knot that can be tied in the bight) in Lester Griswold's book, "Handicraft"; but Drew did not show it in his on book of knots later published.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The method shown below is the most basic way to tie the knot around a post (that is, using a working end).
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Pass the working end over the standing part and then under the riding turn and standing part, forming an overhand knot under a riding turn.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Be sure the ends emerge between the two turns as shown.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] There are also at least three methods to tie the constrictor knot in the bight and slip it over the end of an object to be bound.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If one or both of the ends are folded in between the two loops and lead in the opposite direction, the knot becomes slipped.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If the rope is to be stretched in tension, the grabbing at stage 2 may first tighten the top side rope, the bottom side rope may be pulled to tighten the knot itself, and the bottom rope side may be tightened by the knot at the next pole.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If one or both of the ends are folded and led in the opposite direction before the last loop is folded over the objects end, the knot becomes slipped and therefore easier to untie: It also makes it possible to stretch either side rope tight by pulling at the slip loops.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If a stronger and even more secure knot is required an extra riding turn can be added to the basic knot to form a double constrictor knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] It is particularly useful when tying the knot with very slippery twine, especially when waxed.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Adding more than one extra riding turn does not add to its security and makes the knot more difficult to tighten evenly.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Pass the working end over the standing part, then thread it back under the standing part and *both* riding turns, forming an overhand knot under two riding turns.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Be sure the ends emerge between the turns as shown.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The double constrictor may require more careful dressing to distribute the tension throughout the knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] After working up fairly tight, pull firmly on the ends to finish.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] This variation is useful if it is known beforehand that the constrictor will need to be released.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Depending on the knotting material and how tightly it is cinched, the slipped form can still be very difficult to release.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Continue around behind the object, and then again over the standing part back to the side of the first turn.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Pass a bight of the working end under the point where the first riding pass and the standing part cross to form a slip loop.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Be sure the slip loop bight and both ends emerge from in between the two turns as shown.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] To release, tug on the working end so that the bight passes back through the knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The slipped constrictor can also be tied in the bight and slipped over the object to constrict.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Despite its advertised advantage (quick release), the slipped constrictor knot can also be hard to release when worked extremely tight in certain rope materials.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] This variation is similar to the double constrictor knot but has the two riding turns crossing each other rather than riding along.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] It is unclear whether it is more secure than the double constrictor, and has the unhelpful aspect of being thicker at the bridge of the knot, with three rope diameters.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] There are two types depending on which direction the two riding turns cross.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] When the bottom riding turn is along the grove of the ends wrapping around each other on their way out, it gives a slightly lower knot height and may be seen as a strangle knot with an extra riding turn across.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The constrictor knot is appropriate for situations where secure temporary or semi-permanent binding is needed.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Made with small-stuff it is especially effective, as the binding force is concentrated over a smaller area.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] When tying over soft material such as the neck of a bag, take care to keep the wraps of the knot together.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The constrictor knot can damage or disfigure items it is tied around.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] To exert extreme tension on the knot without injuring the hands, one can fashion handles using marlinespike hitches made around two rods.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Constrictor knots can be used for temporarily binding the fibres of a rope (or strand ends) together while splicing, or when cutting to length and before properly whipping the ends.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Constrictor knots can also be quite effective as improvised hose clamps or cable ties.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The knot has also been recommended as a surgical knot for ligatures in human and veterinary surgery, where it has been shown to be far superior to any of the knots commonly used for ligation.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] For spearguns, the constrictor knot is the usual knot used to secure modern, toggled, Dyneema, cord wishbones into the hollow, bulk-rubber loops, which are used to power the spear.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Usually tied with braid, Kevlar or Dyneema cord of approximately 1.4-2mm diameter.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] A heavily tightened constrictor knot will likely jam.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If the ends are long enough, one can sometimes untie it by pulling one end generally parallel to the bound object and a bit up away from it, and prying it into the opposite end's part to open the knot.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Tools that can be forced between parts of the knot (such as picks and marlinespikes) may help.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If the ends have been trimmed short, or the knot is otherwise hopelessly jammed, it can be easily released by cutting the riding turn with a sharp knife.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The knot will spring apart as soon as the riding turn is cut.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If care is taken not to cut too deeply, the underlying wraps will protect the bound object from being damaged by the knife.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] The constrictor and double constrictor are both extremely secure when tied tightly around convex objects with cord scaled for the task at hand.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If binding around a not fully convex, or square-edged object, arrange the knot so the overhand knot portion is stretched across a convex portion, or a corner, with the riding turn directly atop it.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] In situations where the object leaves gaps under the knot and there are no corners, it is possible to finish the constrictor knot off with an additional overhand knot, in the fashion of a reef knot, to help stabilize it.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] Those recommendations aside, constrictor knots do function best on fully convex objects.
[src:cable-tie/constrictor-knot] If the constricted object (such as a temporarily whipped rope) ends very close to where a constrictor binds it, a boa knot may prove a more stable solution.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE is resistant to acids at high concentrations and temperatures, caustic media, oxidizing agents, and many solvents.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Its chemical resistance is similar to that of PTFE.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Permeation of this polymer by large molecules is slow and thus is not relevant in final applications.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Small molecules, however, may permeate through the polymer matrix.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] In lining or coating applications using ECTFE, permeability of certain small molecules determines the lifetime of anti-corrosion protection.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Small molecules such as H2O, O2, Cl2, H2S, HCl, HF, HBr, N2, H2, and CH3OH are relatively mobile in the polymer matrix and lead to measurable effects.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Permeation resistance of the polymer is critical for lining and coating applications because permeating species may attack the underlying mechanical layers, such as fibre-reinforced plastic (FRP) or steel.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] High permeation resistance to small molecules is a consequence of the free volume occupied by the chlorine atoms in the polymer chain.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE has a continuous usage temperature range between –76°C and +150°C (–105°F to +300°F).
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] It has strong impact resistance and a Young's modulus in the range of 1700 MPa, allowing for self-standing items and pressure piping systems.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] The polymer maintains high impact strength in cryogenic applications.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] In terms of fire resistance, ECTFE shows a limiting oxygen index of 52%.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] This value places it between the fully fluorinated polymers PTFE, PFA, and FEP with a limiting oxygen index of 95% and other partially fluorinated polymers like PVDF with a limiting oxygen index of 44% or ETFE with a limiting oxygen index of 30%.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE acts as an electrical insulator, with high resistivity and a low dielectric constant as well as a low dissipation factor, allowing its use for wire and cable primary and secondary jacketing.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE has good ultraviolet (UV) resistance, in particular against UV-A and UV-B.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Films made of the polymer can be transparent.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE powder is most commonly used in electrostatic powder coating.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Such coatings have a typical thickness of 0.8 mm but can be applied up to 2 mm with a special grade for high build up.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Extrusion of ECTFE fabric-backed sheets and subsequent fabrication into vessels, pipes or valves is done in the chemical industry.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Thick sheets are compression molded and can be manufactured to 50 mm in thickness.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] They are used in the semiconductor industry for wet benches or machining other parts.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE has been widely used in the semiconductor industry for wet tool and tubing systems for lithographic chemicals.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] It is also used in the pharmaceutical industry.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE is used for primary and secondary jacketing in specialty cables like data cables or self-regulating heating cables, applications where good fire resistance and electrical properties are key properties.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] It is also used for braiding in that field.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE in the form of a monofilament fiber is used in flue gas treatment and in certain chemical processes.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Unlike PTFE, ECTFE can be crimped, which allows its production in the form of nonwoven fibers with high surface area and porosity.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] Even though such material has low chemical reactivity, ECTFE in general has somewhat lower chemical resistance compared to PTFE.
[src:cable-tie/ectfe] ECTFE is used for manufacturing gaskets to store liquid oxygen and other propellants for aerospace applications.
